55
00:03:48,093 --> 00:03:49,685
and Poppy Carnahan.

56
00:03:49,762 --> 00:03:51,957
Charmed, charmed, charmed.

57
00:03:52,031 --> 00:03:54,499
We're drinking champagne
in honor of the occasion.

58
00:03:54,566 --> 00:03:56,796
Have you seen the <i>Herald?</i>

59
00:03:56,869 --> 00:03:57,995
Not yet.

60
00:03:58,070 --> 00:03:59,367
I won't embarrass you,

61
00:03:59,438 --> 00:04:01,531
but Caven could
hardly contain himself.

62
00:04:01,607 --> 00:04:02,631
More important,

63
00:04:02,708 --> 00:04:05,006
Richard and Poppy here loved the play.

64
00:04:05,077 --> 00:04:06,169
Weeping.

65
00:04:06,245 --> 00:04:07,177
Copious tears.

66
00:04:07,246 --> 00:04:09,373
What did the <i>Herald</i> say?

67
00:04:09,448 --> 00:04:10,710
I happen to have it.

68
00:04:10,783 --> 00:04:11,750
Please, Derek...

69
00:04:11,817 --> 00:04:13,284
<i>"Bare Ruined Choirs:</i>

70
00:04:13,352 --> 00:04:15,820
<i>Triumph of the Common Man.</i>

71
00:04:15,888 --> 00:04:18,083
The star of <i>Bare Ruined Choirs</i>

72
00:04:18,157 --> 00:04:20,489
was nowhere seen
on the stage last night,

73
00:04:20,559 --> 00:04:22,823
though the thespians
acquitted themselves admirably.

74
00:04:22,895 --> 00:04:24,658
The find of the evening

75
00:04:24,730 --> 00:04:27,699
was the author of this drama
about simple folk,

76
00:04:27,766 --> 00:04:29,165
fishmongers, in fact,

77
00:04:29,234 --> 00:04:30,963
whose brute struggle for existence

78
00:04:31,036 --> 00:04:33,664
cannot quite quell their longing
for something higher.

79
00:04:33,739 --> 00:04:35,172
The playwright finds nobility

80
00:04:35,240 --> 00:04:37,037
in the most squalid corners

81
00:04:37,109 --> 00:04:39,737
and poetry in the most callous speech.

82
00:04:39,812 --> 00:04:42,838
A tough new voice
in the American theater has arrived,

83
00:04:42,915 --> 00:04:45,349
and the owner of that voice is named...

84
00:04:45,417 --> 00:04:47,351
Barton Fink."

85
00:04:47,419 --> 00:04:51,150
They'll be wrapping fish in it
in the morning.

86
00:04:51,223 --> 00:04:53,020
Cynic.

87
00:04:53,092 --> 00:04:55,720
I can't start listening to the critics,

88
00:04:55,794 --> 00:04:58,695
and I can't kid myself
about my own work.

89
00:04:58,764 --> 00:05:00,698
A writer writes from his gut.

90
00:05:00,766 --> 00:05:03,735
His gut tells him
what's good and what's...

91
00:05:03,802 --> 00:05:05,702
merely adequate.

92
00:05:06,939 --> 00:05:09,874
I don't pretend to be a critic,

93
00:05:09,942 --> 00:05:12,467
but Lord knows I have a gut,

94
00:05:12,544 --> 00:05:16,036
and my gut tells me it's simply...

95
00:05:16,115 --> 00:05:18,174
marvelous.

96
00:05:18,250 --> 00:05:20,582
And a charming gut it is.

97
00:05:20,652 --> 00:05:22,483
Oh, you dog.

98
00:05:22,554 --> 00:05:24,613
Aroo!

99
00:05:24,690 --> 00:05:26,021
Oh, stop.

100
00:05:26,091 --> 00:05:27,888
[BellJingles]

101
00:05:31,497 --> 00:05:34,398
I thought you were going to join us.

102
00:05:34,466 --> 00:05:37,526
Jesus, Garland,
you left me alone with those people?

103
00:05:37,603 --> 00:05:38,661
Don't panic.

104
00:05:38,737 --> 00:05:40,864
I'll join you in a minute.

105
00:05:40,939 --> 00:05:43,499
We have to talk a little business.

106
00:05:43,575 --> 00:05:46,510
I've just been on the phone
to Los Angeles.

107
00:05:46,578 --> 00:05:49,513
Barton, Capitol Pictures wants to
put you under contract.

108
00:05:49,581 --> 00:05:52,015
They've offered you $1,000 a week.

109
00:05:52,084 --> 00:05:55,019
I think I can get them
to go as high as 2.

110
00:05:55,087 --> 00:05:56,349
To do what?

111
00:05:56,422 --> 00:05:58,652
What do you do for a living?

112
00:05:58,724 --> 00:06:00,521
I'm not sure anymore.

113
00:06:00,592 --> 00:06:03,993
I guess I try to make a difference.

114
00:06:04,062 --> 00:06:07,122
There's no pressure here
because I respect you,

115
00:06:07,199 --> 00:06:09,394
but a brief tenure in Hollywood

116
00:06:09,468 --> 00:06:11,663
could support you through the writing

117
00:06:11,737 --> 00:06:13,500
of any number of plays.

118
00:06:13,572 --> 00:06:15,005
I don't know, Garland.

119
00:06:15,073 --> 00:06:17,303
My place is here right now.

120
00:06:17,376 --> 00:06:20,140
I feel I'm on the brink of success.

121
00:06:20,212 --> 00:06:22,510
I'd say you're already enjoying some.

122
00:06:22,581 --> 00:06:24,173
No. Don't you see?

123
00:06:24,249 --> 00:06:27,150
Not the kind of success
where critics fawn over you

124
00:06:27,219 --> 00:06:29,983
or producers like Derek
make a lot of money.

125
00:06:30,055 --> 00:06:31,852
No. A real success.

126
00:06:31,924 --> 00:06:33,983
The success we've been dreaming about...

127
00:06:34,059 --> 00:06:36,994
the creation of a new living theater

128
00:06:37,062 --> 00:06:40,054
of and about and for the common man.

129
00:06:40,132 --> 00:06:42,600
If I ran off to Hollywood now,

130
00:06:42,668 --> 00:06:44,067
I'd be making money,

131
00:06:44,136 --> 00:06:46,001
going to parties,
meeting the big shots,

132
00:06:46,071 --> 00:06:47,834
but I'd be cutting myself off

133
00:06:47,906 --> 00:06:50,204
from the wellspring of that success,

134
00:06:50,275 --> 00:06:51,867
from the common man.

135
00:06:54,012 --> 00:06:57,778
Oh, I guess I'm spouting off again.

136
00:06:57,850 --> 00:06:59,579
You see Caven's review?

137
00:06:59,651 --> 00:07:01,346
No. What did it say?

138
00:07:01,420 --> 00:07:02,887
Here, take my copy.

139
00:07:02,955 --> 00:07:04,786
You're the toast of Broadway,

140
00:07:04,857 --> 00:07:06,620
and you have an opportunity

141
00:07:06,692 --> 00:07:10,093
to redeem that for a little cash...

142
00:07:10,162 --> 00:07:12,426
Strike that.
A lot of cash.

143
00:07:12,498 --> 00:07:17,492
The common man will still be here
when you get back.

144
00:07:17,569 --> 00:07:18,968
Who knows?

145
00:07:19,037 --> 00:07:22,473
They may even have one or two of them
out in Hollywood.

146
00:07:22,541 --> 00:07:25,169
That's a rationalization, Garland.

147
00:07:25,244 --> 00:07:29,578
Barton, it was a joke.

